"""
mkt-context Layer — Exodus chapters 7–9
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-exodus-7-9-fill.py

Key historical/ANE context decisions:
- The ten plagues as a systematic assault on the Egyptian pantheon (Exod 12:12 declares this
  explicitly); each plague targets one or more Egyptian deities in their area of jurisdiction.
- Ch 7: chartumim = Egyptian lector priests (kher-heb); the Nile as Osiris/Hapy/Khnum's domain;
  blood plague targets Hapy (Nile fertility god) and Khnum (Nile source guardian at Elephantine);
  the Ipuwer Papyrus (disputed connection) mentions 'the river is blood.'
- Ch 8: Heqet (frog goddess of fertility and childbirth) inverted; the kinnim identity debate
  (gnats/lice/gnats — the Egyptian word snm = lice favored; 'finger of God' as the magicians'
  admission); the Goshen distinction begins at the fly/arov plague (v.22).
- Ch 9: Apis bull and Hathor cow cults targeted by livestock plague; the boils incapacitate
  the magicians (their last appearance); the agricultural chronology of the hail plague
  (flax in bud + barley in ear = February-March, one month before Passover);
  moral discrimination at v.20 — Egyptians who feared YHWH survived.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CONTEXT = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p><b>'See, I have made you as God (elohim) to Pharaoh':</b> The divine commission sets the epistemological frame for the plague narrative. In Egyptian theology, Pharaoh was not merely a human king but the divine son of Ra, the living Horus, god incarnate — the absolute divine-human mediator. By making Moses 'as God to Pharaoh,' YHWH posits a counter-authority to Pharaoh's divine claim: the God of the Hebrew slaves outranks the god-king of Egypt. This verse establishes the plague cycle as a theological duel between competing divine claims, not merely a political liberation movement.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>Aaron your brother shall tell Pharaoh to let the people of Israel go:</b> The Moses-Aaron spokesman chain mirrors the Egyptian royal court structure in which a herald (wpwty) announced decrees on behalf of the pharaoh. Aaron functions as Moses's wpwty before Pharaoh's court. The Egyptian royal court was an elaborate ceremonial institution in which direct access to Pharaoh was rare; approaching through a herald/spokesman was the normal protocol for formal audiences.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>I will harden Pharaoh's heart, and though I multiply my signs (otot) and wonders (moftim) in the land of Egypt:</b> The otot (signs) and moftim (portents/wonders) vocabulary is the standard ANE language for acts of divine power that demonstrate a deity's sovereignty; Egyptian royal ideology used similar vocabulary for the pharaoh's military and cultic accomplishments — carved on temple walls as evidence of divine mandate. YHWH's signs directly compete with the pharaonic claims. The Merneptah Stele (c. 1208 BCE) uses similar triumph language: gods demonstrated their power through chosen kings.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>Pharaoh will not listen to you. Then I will lay my hand on Egypt and bring out my hosts (tzivotai), my people the children of Israel, by great acts of judgment:</b> Tzivotai = my armies/hosts (from tzava = army; the same root as tzabaot in 'YHWH of Hosts'); Israel is YHWH's army, organized for departure as a military force. The 'hand of YHWH' (yad YHWH) is both an idiom for divine power and a military metaphor — the god who strikes with his 'hand' in battle. Egyptian royal inscriptions describe the pharaoh's victories as the 'strong arm' (hand) of Amun or Ra.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>The Egyptians shall know that I am YHWH (yede'u Mitzrayim ki ani YHWH) when I stretch out my hand over Egypt:</b> The da'at formula ('shall know that I am YHWH') appears seven times in chapters 7-14 — a deliberate sevenfold pattern. Egypt's knowledge of YHWH is the stated divine purpose of the plagues. The Egyptian concept of knowledge of a deity (rx) was equally important; to know the true name and power of a deity was the basis of religious authority. YHWH is asserting that Egypt will come to know a superior divine power through the plagues.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>Moses and Aaron did so; as YHWH commanded them, so they did:</b> The compliance formula (ka'asher tzivah YHWH... ken asu) appears throughout chapters 36-40 for the tabernacle construction and here at the start of the plague cycle — the same language of complete obedience. The plague narrative is framed as executed instructions, not improvised responses.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>Moses was eighty years old, and Aaron eighty-three years old, when they spoke to Pharaoh:</b> The ages situate Moses and Aaron in the generational context: they belong to the generation born under the initial oppression (after Pharaoh's death decree for Hebrew male infants). Moses's 40 years in Midian (Acts 7:23,30 supplies the 40+40 framework) + 40 in Egypt = 80 at the Exodus. The age information is unusual in narrative contexts — it emphasizes that these are not young men but seasoned lives being used by YHWH for this specific moment.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses and Aaron, 'When Pharaoh says to you, Give us a sign (mofet), then you shall say to Aaron, Take your staff':</b> The demand for a mofet (portent/sign) was standard in Egyptian royal audiences — a claimant to divine authority was expected to demonstrate it through a miraculous sign. Egyptian texts describe various signs performed by priests and magicians. The serpent sign was chosen deliberately: the uraeus serpent (the cobra worn on Pharaoh's crown) was the symbol of royal divine authority. Aaron's staff-turned-serpent challenges Pharaoh's own emblem of divine power.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>Aaron's staff became a serpent (nachash):</b> The word nachash (serpent) connects to the Eden serpent (Gen 3) and to the bronze serpent of Numbers 21. The Egyptian word for the royal cobra on Pharaoh's crown was 'iaret' (uraeus); the cobra was sacred to Wadjet, the protective goddess of Lower Egypt. Aaron's serpent represents a counter-claim to the cobra-power of the Egyptian crown. The transformation of a staff into a snake was also known in Egyptian magical literature — the magicians' ability to replicate it means the sign was within the range of known Egyptian magic.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>Moses and Aaron went to Pharaoh and did just as YHWH commanded:</b> The royal audience with Pharaoh takes place in a context of high Egyptian ceremony. The court of the pharaoh was among the most elaborate bureaucratic and ceremonial institutions in the ancient world; entering it required protocol. Moses and Aaron stand before a court that considers itself the center of the cosmos — the son of Ra surrounded by his divine court officials.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>Then Pharaoh also called the wise men and the sorcerers, and they also, the magicians (chartumim) of Egypt, did the same with their secret arts (lehateichem):</b> Chartumim = the Hebrew transliteration of the Egyptian 'kher-heb' (chief ritual lector priests — the priests who recited ritual texts from papyrus scrolls during religious ceremonies). These were not carnival tricksters but the highest-ranking ritual specialists in Egyptian religion. In 2 Timothy 3:8 they are named as Jannes and Jambres (a tradition preserved in later Jewish texts including the Damascus Document). Lahat (secret arts/occult craft) is the same word used for the flaming sword guarding Eden (Gen 3:24).</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>For each man cast down his staff and they became serpents. But Aaron's staff swallowed up their staffs:</b> The magicians could replicate the sign — but Aaron's serpent ate theirs. The swallowing (bala') is the decisive indicator: YHWH's representative does not merely match the Egyptian priests but surpasses and consumes their power. The competitive swallowing may reflect the Egyptian cosmological concept of divine power establishing supremacy by consuming a rival deity's manifestation.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>Still Pharaoh's heart was hardened, and he would not listen to them, as YHWH had said:</b> Pharaoh interprets the result favorably for his own side — the magicians matched the sign, so the overall event is a draw that justifies maintaining his position. This is the first of 10 hardenings in chapters 7-14. The hardening of Pharaoh's heart is both a theological description (YHWH's sovereignty over history) and a psychological description (Pharaoh's own confirmation bias).</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Pharaoh's heart is heavy (kaveid):'</b> Kaveid (heavy) is the Qal stative of kavad (the same root as kavod = glory). Pharaoh's heavy heart is the anti-glory — the weight that refuses to respond to the divine summons. The Egyptians believed the heart (ib) was weighed by Anubis after death against the feather of Ma'at (truth/justice); a heart too heavy with sin failed the judgment. Pharaoh's kaveid heart anticipates its own eschatological verdict.</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>Go to Pharaoh in the morning, as he is going out to the water:</b> Pharaoh's morning visit to the Nile was likely a religious ritual — the pharaoh participated in daily worship ceremonies, and the Nile held special cultic significance. Egyptian inscriptions describe pharaohs performing rites at the Nile's edge. The instruction to intercept Pharaoh at the water is a deliberate choice of venue: the confrontation happens at the Nile, which is the first target of the plague.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>'The LORD, the God of the Hebrews, has sent me to you, saying, Let my people go, that they may serve me in the wilderness:'</b> The repeated identification 'YHWH God of the Hebrews' (YHWH elohei ha-Ivrim) defines YHWH as the deity specifically associated with the Hebrew people — from Egypt's perspective, a tribal deity of slave laborers, not a universal sovereign. The plagues systematically demonstrate that this 'tribal deity' controls every dimension of Egyptian reality.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>'I will strike the water of the Nile (y'or) with the staff, and it shall turn to blood:'</b> Y'or = the Nile (the Egyptian word 'Itrw' = the River, borrowed into Hebrew as y'or; the Nile is never called a river by its generic name but always y'or in Exodus). The Nile was Egypt's lifeline — the source of water, food, transportation, and the annual flood that fertilized the fields. Striking the Nile was striking Egypt's foundational life-support system. The blood transformation targeted Hapy (the Nile-flood deity of abundance), Khnum (creator god and guardian of the Nile's sources at the First Cataract/Elephantine), and Osiris (in some traditions the Nile itself was Osiris's blood flowing through Egypt).</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>'The fish in the Nile shall die, and the Nile shall stink, and the Egyptians will grow weary of drinking water from the Nile:'</b> Fish were a major protein source for Egyptians of all classes; Egyptian art frequently depicts fishing in the Nile. The death of the fish would cause a significant food crisis independent of the water pollution. 'The Egyptians will grow weary (nile'u)' — the same word used in Exod 7:24 (they dug along the Nile) and in 18:18 (you will surely wear out). The plague creates a weariness that anticipates eventual capitulation.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>'Say to Aaron, Take your staff and stretch out your hand over the waters of Egypt, over their rivers, their canals, and their ponds, and all their pools of water, so that they may become blood:'</b> The comprehensive list (y'orot = Nile branches; ye'orim = canals; agamim = ponds; mikveh ha-mayim = reservoirs/pools) ensures the plague covers Egypt's entire water system. Egypt's hydraulic infrastructure was extensive: the Nile's multiple branches in the Delta, irrigation canals throughout the cultivated land, fish ponds, and storage cisterns — all affected.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>Moses and Aaron did as YHWH commanded. In the sight of Pharaoh and in the sight of his servants he lifted up the staff and struck the water in the Nile, and all the water in the Nile turned into blood:</b> The public performance of the sign 'in the sight of Pharaoh and his servants' is deliberate. Egyptian inscriptions and tomb paintings regularly describe pharaonic and priestly acts performed before witnesses to validate them. The plague is a public theological demonstration, not a private miracle.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>And the fish in the Nile died, and the Nile stank, so that the Egyptians could not drink water from the Nile:</b> The Nile's stench would have been catastrophic in a civilization where the Nile's smell was associated with fertility and abundance; the smell of the inundation was culturally positive. The inversion of the Nile's characteristic scent into a stench is a sensory reversal of Egypt's fundamental relationship with its river. Ancient Egyptians described the Nile flood as 'the perfume of the gods' — now it smells of death.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>But the magicians of Egypt did the same by their secret arts. So Pharaoh's heart remained hardened, and he would not listen to them, as YHWH had said:</b> The magicians replicating the blood plague is often cited as evidence of limited occult power — but the theological point is that their replication made the situation worse (more blood, not less). They could not reverse the plague; they could only add to it. Pharaoh uses their replication as cover for continued refusal. Egyptian records do describe magical rituals involving blood symbolism in apotropaic contexts.</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>Pharaoh turned and went into his house, and he did not take even this to heart:</b> The Egyptian idiom for unresponsiveness to a divine sign would have been understood as a failure of ma'at — pharaoh's obligation to maintain cosmic order required responsiveness to divine communications. Pharaoh's dismissal of YHWH's sign is simultaneously a failure of his theological obligation and an act of political defiance.</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>And all the Egyptians dug along the Nile for water to drink, for they could not drink the water of the Nile:</b> Archaeological evidence shows the ancient Egyptians were highly skilled at finding groundwater; shallow wells in the Nile basin floor could yield potable water even when the surface water was polluted. The Egyptians' ingenuity in bypassing the plague (digging for filtered groundwater) is consistent with the practical resourcefulness shown throughout Egyptian history in managing their water resources.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>Seven full days passed after YHWH had struck the Nile:</b> The seven-day duration of the first plague before the second begins is the only explicit plague duration given in the narrative. Seven days = one week = the complete creation unit. The plague lasted long enough to be taken seriously but ended before it permanently destroyed Egypt's water system. The temporal structure of the plagues (plague → hardening → relief → new plague) creates a rhythmic escalation that gives Pharaoh repeated opportunities to respond.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Go in to Pharaoh and say to him, Thus says YHWH, Let my people go, that they may serve me. But if you refuse to let them go, behold, I will plague all your country with frogs (tz'phardea):'</b> Tz'phardea = frog (Egyptian: qrr or krr; the frog was sacred in Egypt as a symbol of fertility and new life). Heqet was the Egyptian frog-headed goddess of childbirth and fertility — the patron deity of the midwives who assisted at birth. The frog plague inverted Heqet's domain: instead of frogs symbolizing the blessing of new life, they became an overwhelming infestation. The midwives (meyaldot) who defied Pharaoh's infanticide command in Exod 1:15-21 may have invoked Heqet's protection; now Heqet's symbol becomes Egypt's plague.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>The Nile shall swarm (sharatz) with frogs that shall come up into your house and into your bedroom and on your bed:</b> Sharatz = to swarm/teem (the same verb as the swarming of sea creatures in Gen 1:20 and the swarming of life in the aftermath of creation). The frog infestation reverses the creation blessing of abundance into a curse of overwhelming proliferation. The specific locations — house, bedroom, bed — represent the private, intimate, and restful spaces of life; the plague penetrates to the innermost domestic spaces that Egyptian architecture was designed to protect.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>The frogs shall come up on you and on your people and on all your servants:</b> The comprehensive social coverage — Pharaoh, his people, all his servants — mirrors the Nile's comprehensive coverage in the first plague. Every social stratum of Egyptian society is affected equally. The equality of the plague's impact across all social classes is itself a theological statement: YHWH's judgment does not respect the social hierarchy Egypt has constructed.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>Then Moses and Aaron went to Pharaoh and said, 'Thus says YHWH, Let my people go that they may serve me':</b> The repeated demand formula (shalach et-ami v'ya'avduni = let my people go that they may serve me) appears in seven of the ten plague cycles. The consistency of the demand throughout the plague narrative demonstrates that the purpose is not punishment but release: each plague is an opportunity for Pharaoh to comply with the original request.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>And YHWH said to Moses, 'Say to Aaron, Stretch out your hand with your staff over the rivers, the canals, and the ponds, and make frogs come up on the land of Egypt':</b> The comprehensive water system of Egypt (rivers/Nile channels, canals, ponds/marshes) is again the source of the plague — the same waters that turned to blood now produce frogs. The sequential use of the same water system for two different plagues establishes the Nile as the primary locus of divine action: Egypt's greatest blessing is YHWH's instrument of judgment.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>So Aaron stretched out his hand over the waters of Egypt, and the frogs came up and covered the land of Egypt:</b> 'Covered the land' (v'takh's ha-tz'pharde'a et-eretz Mitzrayim) uses the same 'cover' (khasa) language as the locust plague (10:15) and the Red Sea covering the Egyptians (14:28). The covering pattern establishes each plague as progressively more total in its coverage.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>But the magicians did the same by their secret arts and made frogs come up on the land of Egypt:</b> Again the chartumim replicate the plague, making the situation worse rather than better. The replication of the frog plague is their final successful imitation; they will fail at the lice plague and be physically incapacitated by the boils. The trajectory of the magicians — capable of replication → unable to replicate → physically defeated — charts Egypt's progressive defeat.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Then Pharaoh called Moses and Aaron and said, 'Plead with YHWH to take away the frogs from me and from my people, and I will let the people go to sacrifice to YHWH':</b> Pharaoh's first prayer request to YHWH through Moses — and his first offer to comply, conditional on relief. This is a significant theological moment: the god-king of Egypt who declared 'Who is YHWH?' (5:2) is now asking YHWH's servants to intercede for him. The frogs in Pharaoh's bed may have been more personally intolerable than the blood in the Nile — the plague penetrated his personal space in a way the water contamination did not.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>Moses said to Pharaoh, 'Be pleased to command me when I am to plead for you and for your servants and for your people, that the frogs be cut off from you and your houses and be left only in the Nile.'</b> Moses's offer to let Pharaoh set the timing of the plague's removal is a diplomatic and theological stratagem — if Moses names the time himself, Pharaoh could claim the cessation was coincidental; if Pharaoh names the time and the frogs stop at exactly that moment, the divine control of the timing is demonstrated. The demonstration of precise divine control over timing is itself a refutation of natural explanations.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>'Tomorrow,' said Pharaoh. And Moses said, 'Be it as you say, so that you may know that there is no one like YHWH our God.'</b> Pharaoh's choice of 'tomorrow' (machar) rather than 'immediately' has puzzled commentators. Possibly: he is buying one more night of comfort (the frogs being marginally preferable to another night of compliance)? Or he does not fully believe Moses can deliver? Or he is testing whether Moses has real control? The result — frogs removed precisely at the time Pharaoh named — proves divine precision.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>The frogs shall go away from you and your houses and your servants and your people. They shall be left only in the Nile.</b> The precision of the divine response — frogs removed except from the Nile — matches the precision of the divine promise. The Nile (the source and proper domain of frogs in Egypt's ecology) retains its frogs; the unnatural infestation is removed, but the natural order is restored. The restoration of normalcy is itself a sign of divine control.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>So Moses and Aaron went out from Pharaoh, and Moses cried to YHWH about the frogs, as he had agreed with Pharaoh:</b> Moses's intercessory prayer (vayyitz'aq Moshe el-YHWH) on behalf of Pharaoh is theologically striking — the prophet of YHWH prays for the relief of YHWH's enemy. The pattern of intercession on behalf of Pharaoh (8:12, 8:28-30, 9:33, 10:18) establishes Moses as a mediator figure who stands between YHWH's justice and human need, even the need of those who oppress his people.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>And YHWH did according to the word of Moses. The frogs died out in the houses, the courtyards, and the fields.</b> The three spatial zones — houses (domestic interior), courtyards (semi-domestic transition space), fields (agricultural exterior) — mark the complete clearing of the plague from the inhabited and agricultural landscape. The precision of the fulfillment (exactly as Pharaoh requested, exactly at the time he named) demonstrates YHWH's sovereign command of natural processes.</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>And they gathered them together in heaps, and the land stank:</b> The decomposing frog carcasses after the plague ended would have created a secondary public health crisis — rotting amphibians in the Egyptian summer heat. The stench (tivash ha'aretz = the land reeked) of the aftermath mirrors the stench of the Nile during the blood plague (7:18,21). The aftermath of each plague is as unpleasant as the plague itself, accumulating pressure on Pharaoh to comply.</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>But when Pharaoh saw that there was a respite, he hardened his heart and would not listen to them, as YHWH had said:</b> The relief-hardening pattern is established here explicitly: Pharaoh's behavioral change was driven entirely by immediate distress, not genuine recognition of YHWH's authority. The psychology of hardening under pressure followed by return to the original position when pressure is removed is a consistent feature of human response to divine discipline that the prophets later address (Isa 26:9-10; Hos 5:15-6:4).</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Say to Aaron, Stretch out your staff and strike the dust of the earth, so that it may become gnats (kinnim) throughout all the land of Egypt.'</b> Kinnim = the third plague; the exact identity of the insect is debated — the Hebrew kinnim appears only in the plague narrative and Ps 105:31; the LXX reads 'gnats' (skniphes); the Vulgate reads 'flies' (sciniphes); the Talmud (Sanhedrin 67b) interprets as lice; the word may be related to the Egyptian word 'snn' for a type of mosquito or sand fly. The distinctive feature of this plague is its origin from the dust (afar ha'aretz) rather than the Nile.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>They did so. Aaron stretched out his hand with his staff and struck the dust of the earth, and there were gnats on man and beast. All the dust of the earth became gnats in all the land of Egypt:</b> The metamorphosis of the dust itself (kol afar ha'aretz hayah kinnim) — not just gnats coming from dust but the dust becoming insects — exceeds anything in the Egyptian magical tradition. The dust-to-insect transformation inverts the creation narrative: in Gen 2:7 YHWH formed Adam from dust (afar) and breathed life into him; here the dust of Egypt produces a pestilential swarm.</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>The magicians tried by their secret arts to produce gnats, but they could not. So there were gnats on man and beast:</b> The chartumim's failure at the lice/gnats plague is the pivotal moment in the Egyptian magicians' story. They have been matching Moses and Aaron plague-for-plague (unsuccessfully, since they can only add to the plagues, not remove them); now they cannot even replicate. Their failure signals a qualitative difference between YHWH's power and Egyptian magic. This is the last plague from which the chartumim attempt replication.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>And the magicians said to Pharaoh, 'This is the finger of God (etzba Elohim).' But Pharaoh's heart was hardened, and he would not listen to them, as YHWH had said:</b> 'Finger of God' (etzba Elohim) — the Egyptian priests' own confession. The term 'finger of God' appears also in Exod 31:18 (the stone tablets written by YHWH's own finger) and Deut 9:10. In Egyptian religious texts, various deities were described as acting through their 'finger' (dba = finger in Egyptian) in magical contexts; the chartumim are using their own theological framework to acknowledge defeat. Notably, they say 'Elohim,' not YHWH — they acknowledge a superior divine power without necessarily identifying it as the Hebrew God by name. Pharaoh dismisses even the testimony of his own elite priests.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Rise up early in the morning and present yourself to Pharaoh, as he goes out to the water, and say to him, Thus says YHWH, Let my people go that they may serve me.'</b> The 'going out to the water' venue recurs (cf. 7:15) — the Nile confrontation is the deliberate setting for the covenant demand, making the declaration of YHWH's sovereign authority at the very site of Egypt's primary deity (the Nile/Hapy). The early morning (hashkem baboqer) intercept catches Pharaoh before his daily business begins, maximizing the disruptive impact of the confrontation.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>'For if you will not let my people go, behold, I will send swarms of flies (arov) on you and your servants and your people, and into your houses. The houses of the Egyptians shall be full of swarms of flies, and also the ground on which they stand.'</b> Arov = the fourth plague's identification is disputed. The LXX reads 'dog-fly' (kunomuia = a particularly vicious biting fly, possibly the Stomoxys calcitrans or a tabanid fly). Others read 'swarms' generally or 'mixture of wild animals.' The most defensible reading is a swarm of biting flies — common in Egypt, especially near the Nile Delta. Khepri (the scarab beetle god) and other insect-associated Egyptian deities are implicitly challenged.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>'But on that day I will set apart (hifleiti) the land of Goshen, where my people dwell, so that no swarms of flies shall be there, that you may know that I am YHWH in the midst of the earth (b'kerev ha'aretz):'</b> The Goshen distinction — the theological watershed of the plague cycle. The selective plague (affecting Egypt but not Goshen) is irrefutable evidence of divine discrimination, ruling out natural explanations. Goshen was located in the eastern Nile Delta region (probably the Wadi Tumilat area); the geographical separation from the main Egyptian population centers makes the distinction spatially verifiable. B'kerev ha'aretz = in the midst of the earth — YHWH's authority is not merely over Israel but over the center of the known world (Egypt).</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>'I will put a division (pedut) between my people and your people. Tomorrow this sign shall happen.'</b> Pedut = ransom/separation/distinction (from padah = to redeem/ransom; the exodus redemption vocabulary infiltrating the plague narrative). The 'division' is not just geographical but redemptive — the separation of Israel from Egypt at the plagues is the same separation as the redemption from slavery. The plague-distinction anticipates the exodus-distinction.</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>And YHWH did so. There came great swarms of flies into the house of Pharaoh and into his servants' houses. Throughout all the land of Egypt the land was ruined (tishachet) because of the swarms of flies:</b> Shachat = to ruin/corrupt/destroy (the same root as the 'corruption' of the earth before the Flood in Gen 6:11-12, and the 'destroyer' (mashchit) who struck Egypt's firstborns in 12:23). The 'ruination' of the land by flies anticipates the final plague's destroyer; the plague cycle is escalating toward the ultimate judgment.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>Then Pharaoh called Moses and Aaron and said, 'Go, sacrifice to your God within the land.'</b> Pharaoh's first counter-offer: sacrifice in Egypt (not 'in the wilderness' as Moses demanded). This is a significant concession — Pharaoh is acknowledging that his people should be allowed to perform YHWH's worship — but a limited one: the worship must happen within Egypt, under Pharaoh's jurisdiction, not in the freedom of the wilderness. The geography of worship matters; worship 'within the land' means worship still under Egyptian political control.</p>",
    "26": "<p><b>But Moses said, 'It would not be right to do so, for the offerings we shall sacrifice to YHWH our God are an abomination (toevah) to the Egyptians.'</b> Toevah = abomination (the word for ritual taboo in Egypt as well as Israel). Egyptian religious practice had strict taboos about animal sacrifice; certain animals sacred to Egyptian deities (cattle, rams, ibises, crocodiles, cats) could not be slaughtered without risking Egyptian violence. Cows were sacred to Hathor; rams to Amun and Khnum; sacrificing such animals in public in Egypt would provoke Egyptian outrage. Moses's refusal is theologically and practically astute — unrestricted Israelite sacrifice in Egypt was genuinely impossible.</p>",
    "27": "<p><b>'We must go three days' journey into the wilderness and sacrifice to YHWH our God as he tells us.'</b> The three-day journey (derekh shloshet yamim bamidbar) has been the consistent request since 3:18 — not a permanent departure but a pilgrimage journey. Three days was a standard travel distance in ancient Near Eastern contexts for a round-trip journey to a sacred site. Whether this was a provisional demand (testing Pharaoh) or the initial phase of a full departure is debated; theologically it establishes the principle that Israelite worship must be geographically outside Egypt's jurisdiction.</p>",
    "28": "<p><b>So Pharaoh said, 'I will let you go to sacrifice to YHWH your God in the wilderness; only you must not go very far away. Plead for me.'</b> Pharaoh's second counter-offer: permission to go, but 'not very far away' (raq haracheiq lo tarbbu lalechet). He is trying to maintain practical control over the departing Israelites by restricting their range. The 'plead for me' (ve'hatiru ba'adee) repeats his earlier prayer-request — Pharaoh is becoming increasingly dependent on Moses's intercession with YHWH even while refusing to fully comply.</p>",
    "29": "<p><b>Moses said, 'Behold, I am going out from you and I will plead with YHWH that the swarms of flies may depart from Pharaoh, from his servants, and from his people, tomorrow. Only let not Pharaoh cheat again (yosef Pharaoh hateil) by not letting the people go to sacrifice to YHWH.'</b> Hateil = to deceive/deal falsely (from talal = to mock/deceive); the diplomatic bluntness — Moses directly charges Pharaoh with deceptive intention before the next plague has even started. The pattern of promised compliance followed by re-hardening has been consistent enough that Moses's warning is based on track record.</p>",
    "30": "<p><b>So Moses went out from Pharaoh and prayed to YHWH:</b> The prayer is again unstated in content — the narrative moves directly from Moses's departure to YHWH's action. The emphasis is not on Moses's prayer-words but on the relationship: Moses prays, YHWH responds. The intimacy of the Moses-YHWH relationship throughout the plague narrative is contrasted with the distant and coercive relationship between Pharaoh and his gods.</p>",
    "31": "<p><b>And YHWH did as Moses asked, and removed the swarms of flies from Pharaoh, from his servants, and from his people; not one remained:</b> The total removal ('not one remained' — lo nish'ar echad) is the same formula used for the total destruction of Egypt's firstborns and charioteers. Each act of divine precision — whether removal of plague or execution of judgment — demonstrates the same total control. The complete removal proves YHWH brought the flies and YHWH removed them.</p>",
    "32": "<p><b>But Pharaoh hardened his heart this time also, and did not let the people go:</b> The seventh hardening. Pharaoh's cycle of distress-promise-relief-hardening is now well established. Egyptian royal ideology would have made capitulation to a foreign deity's demands extremely costly politically — every concession to YHWH was a public acknowledgment of Egyptian divine failure. The political stakes of Pharaoh's religious stubbornness are not separable from the theological ones.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Go in to Pharaoh and say to him, Thus says YHWH, the God of the Hebrews, Let my people go, that they may serve me.'</b> The fifth plague opens with the full formal title 'YHWH God of the Hebrews' (YHWH elohei ha-Ivrim) — the same identification used in the first formal confrontation (3:18, 5:3, 7:16). The repeated formula after each rejection maintains the official character of the confrontation: this is a formal divine demand, not a negotiation.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>'For if you refuse to let them go and still hold them, behold, the hand of YHWH (yad YHWH) will fall on your livestock in the field, the horses, the donkeys, the camels, the herds, and the flocks — a very severe plague (dever).'</b> Dever = pestilence/plague (a word used for epidemic disease throughout the OT; cf. Ps 91:3,6). The livestock targeted include horses (susim) — Egypt's military technology — donkeys (chamorim), camels (g'malim), cattle (baqar), and flocks (tzon). The Egyptian economy was deeply dependent on livestock: cattle for agriculture, donkeys for transport, horses for military chariots. The plague's economic implications extended far beyond the immediate animal deaths.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>'Behold, the hand of YHWH will fall (hoyah yad YHWH) on your livestock in the field — a very severe plague.'</b> The livestock plague targeted Egyptian animal cults directly. The Apis bull (Hapi = the sacred black-and-white bull kept at Memphis, associated with Ptah) was Egypt's most important sacred animal; its death would have been the most culturally shocking component of the plague. Hathor (cow goddess of love, beauty, and fertility) and Khnum (ram-headed creator god) were also challenged by a plague killing cattle and sheep.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>'But YHWH will make a distinction (hifla YHWH) between the livestock of Israel and the livestock of Egypt, so that nothing of all that belongs to the people of Israel shall die.'</b> The Goshen distinction (established at the fly plague) is now explicitly applied to the livestock plague. The statistical impossibility of a cattle plague that kills Egyptian livestock but spares geographically adjacent Israelite livestock in Goshen is the evidential heart of the plague's theological claim: natural epidemics do not discriminate by covenant status.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>And YHWH set a time, saying, 'Tomorrow YHWH will do this thing in the land.'</b> The explicit advance announcement of timing (machar — tomorrow) escalates the theological precision: YHWH not only causes the plague but announces its precise start date. Pharaoh cannot claim ignorance of the source or coincidence of the timing. The time-announcement is a form of prophetic certitude: what YHWH declares will happen at the stated time.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>And the next day YHWH did this thing. All the livestock of the Egyptians died, but not one of the livestock of the people of Israel died:</b> The total Egyptian livestock death and the total Israelite survival are each emphasized with 'all' (kol) and 'not one' (lo echad). The absolute nature of both statistics rules out partial natural explanations. The livestock census of ancient Egypt (documented in administrative papyri) shows the scale of Egypt's cattle industry — the loss of all livestock would have been an economic catastrophe of the first magnitude.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>And Pharaoh sent (vayyishlach), and behold, not one of the livestock of Israel was dead. But the heart of Pharaoh was hardened, and he did not let the people go:</b> Pharaoh personally investigates the report of Israelite livestock survival — and confirms it. The investigation (vayyishlach = he sent, presumably investigators to check) and the verification (hinneh lo-met mimikneh Yisrael ad-echad = not one of Israel's livestock was dead) makes the eighth hardening the most theologically stark. Pharaoh has personally verified the divine distinction; he has received empirical confirmation of YHWH's covenant-specific sovereignty. His continued refusal is not ignorance but defiance in the face of evidence.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>And YHWH said to Moses and Aaron, 'Take handfuls of soot from the kiln (pich hakivshan), and let Moses throw it in the air in the sight of Pharaoh.'</b> Pich = soot (from an Egyptian loanword connected to furnace carbon deposits); kivshan = kiln/furnace (the same word as the 'smoking furnace' of Gen 15:17 in the Abrahamic covenant vision). The soot from an Egyptian kiln (possibly a lime-kiln or metal-smelting furnace — Egypt had extensive metallurgical operations near the Delta) thrown into the air is the ritual act that precipitates the boils. The use of soot from an Egyptian industrial furnace is symbolically appropriate: Egypt's industry produces its own plague.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>'And it shall become fine dust (avaq) over all the land of Egypt, and become boils (sh'chin) breaking out in sores on man and beast throughout all the land of Egypt.'</b> Avaq = fine dust (the word for the dust kicked up by armies and whirlwinds in prophetic texts — Isa 5:24; Nah 1:3); the soot becomes fine dust and covers Egypt. Sh'chin = boils/skin eruptions (the medical condition that afflicts Job in 2:7-8 and is listed among the Deuteronomic curses in Deut 28:27,35). The exact condition described (boils breaking into blisters) is consistent with anthrax, smallpox, or a secondary skin infection following livestock disease — the progression from cattle pestilence (plague 5) to human skin disease (plague 6) follows an epidemiologically plausible sequence.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>So they took soot from the kiln and stood before Pharaoh. And Moses threw it in the air, and it became boils breaking out in sores on man and beast:</b> The brevity of the execution narrative (three verbs: took, stood, threw) contrasts with the detailed instruction of v.8-9, emphasizing the total compliance and immediate divine response. No Aaron involvement is mentioned here — the sixth plague is Moses's alone, perhaps foreshadowing the increasing directness of divine action as the plagues escalate.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>And the magicians could not stand before Moses because of the boils, for the boils came upon the magicians and upon all the Egyptians:</b> The chartumim make their final appearance in the plague narrative, physically defeated. The irony: the priests who tried to counter YHWH's plagues by replicating them are now unable to stand (yakhal la'amod lifnei Moshe) because they are afflicted by the very plagues they attempted to contest. Their incapacity is the decisive sign of the end of Egyptian magical counter-resistance. They will not appear again in the Exodus narrative.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>But YHWH hardened the heart of Pharaoh, and he did not listen to them, as YHWH had spoken to Moses:</b> The sixth plague's hardening is the first in the narrative attributed solely and explicitly to YHWH (without any mention of Pharaoh's own action). The earlier hardenings alternated between Pharaoh's self-hardening and YHWH's hardening; from here forward the divine agency in Pharaoh's hardening is emphasized. Paul cites this specific verse (Rom 9:17) to discuss divine sovereignty in election and hardening.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Rise up early in the morning and present yourself before Pharaoh and say to him, Thus says YHWH, the God of the Hebrews, Let my people go, that they may serve me.'</b> The seventh plague warning begins with the most extended divine speech of the plague cycle (vv.13-19), including a theological explanation of why the plagues are occurring and why Pharaoh has not been destroyed already. This expansion in the middle of the plague cycle is the theological center of the entire narrative.</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>'For this time I will send all my plagues (mageyfotai) on you yourself, and on your servants and your people, so that you may know that there is none like me in all the earth.'</b> 'None like me in all the earth' (ein kamoni b'chol-ha'aretz) — the incomparability formula that will appear in the Song of the Sea (mi-kamokha ba'elim YHWH = who is like you among the gods, 15:11). The seventh plague introduces a new intensity: previous plagues targeted Egypt; now the plagues are aimed 'at your heart' (el-libecha). The heart of Pharaoh has been the battleground since the first hardening — now YHWH states explicitly that the purpose is to reach that heart.</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>'For by now I could have put out my hand and struck you and your people with pestilence, and you would have been cut off from the earth.'</b> The counterfactual — 'by now I could have destroyed you' — is a remarkable divine admission. YHWH is not at the limit of his power; he has been restraining himself. The reason Pharaoh is still alive is not Pharaoh's resilience but YHWH's purpose (v.16). This verse is Paul's other citation from the Exodus plague narrative (Rom 9:17) alongside v.12 — the two verses together form Paul's argument for divine sovereignty in mercy and hardening.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>'But for this purpose I have raised you up (he'emadticha), to show you my power, so that my name may be proclaimed in all the earth.'</b> He'emadticha = I have caused you to stand/raised you up (Hiphil of amad); Paul cites this as 'for this purpose I raised you up' (eis touto se exegeira, Rom 9:17). The purpose of Pharaoh's existence — from YHWH's perspective — is to demonstrate divine power before the watching world. The proclamation of YHWH's name 'in all the earth' anticipates the nations' trembling at the news of the Exodus (15:14-16) and Rahab's confession in Josh 2:10-11.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>'You are still exalting yourself (mistalea) against my people and will not let them go.'</b> Sala' = to exalt/lift oneself up (a rare Hithpael form, used for arrogant self-elevation); the language of Egyptian royal ideology inverted — Pharaoh who presents himself as the exalted one (the divine elevation of the pharaoh was expressed in his crown, his titles, his elevated throne) is charged with illegitimate self-exaltation against YHWH. The contrast between YHWH's exaltation (15:1 — ga'oh ga'ah) and Pharaoh's arrogant self-elevation is the theological core of the plague narrative.</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>'Behold, about this time tomorrow I will cause very heavy hail to fall, such as never has been in Egypt from the day it was founded until now.'</b> Egypt's climate makes severe hailstorms very rare — the Nile Delta receives minimal rainfall and even less in the form of hail; genuine hailstorms are almost unknown in Upper Egypt. The hail plague is climatologically anomalous for Egypt in a way it would not be in Canaan or Mesopotamia. The 'never before' (asher lo-hayah kamohoo b'Mitzrayim) superlative places this plague outside the range of known Egyptian experience.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>'Now therefore send, get your livestock and all that you have in the field into safe shelter, for every man and beast that is in the field and is not brought home will die when the hail falls on them.'</b> The advance warning with an opportunity for mitigation is unique among the plagues (except the Passover, where YHWH also provides specific protective instructions). The moral dimension: those Egyptians who took the warning seriously and protected their servants and livestock survived; those who ignored it did not. YHWH's judgment includes an escape clause for those who respond in faith, even within Egypt.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>Then whoever feared the word of YHWH among the servants of Pharaoh hurried his slaves and his livestock into the houses:</b> 'Whoever feared the word of YHWH among the servants of Pharaoh' — Egyptians who believed YHWH. This is the first mention of faith in YHWH among non-Israelites during the plague cycle. Their fear and response anticipates the 'mixed multitude' (erev rav) of 12:38 who left Egypt with Israel. YHWH's offer of protection extended to any Egyptian who took his word seriously — the plague was not inexorably universal for every individual in Egypt.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>But whoever did not pay attention to the word of YHWH left his slaves and his livestock in the field:</b> The two-way response to the divine warning establishes the plagues as a morally serious divine communication, not merely an impersonal natural disaster. Those who ignored the warning suffered the consequences of their own choice. The text is careful to distribute moral responsibility: some Egyptians responded in faith; some did not. The judgment falls on those who reject the warning, not on an undifferentiated 'Egypt.'</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>Then YHWH said to Moses, 'Stretch out your hand toward heaven, so that there may be hail in all the land of Egypt, on man and beast and every plant of the field, in the land of Egypt.'</b> The gesture toward heaven (shamayim) is new — previous plague gestures were toward the water (Nile) or the earth (dust). The hail plague comes from above, from the sky (nut's domain in Egyptian cosmology). Nut (sky goddess), Shu (god of air), and Tefnut (goddess of moisture) are the Egyptian deities of the atmospheric realm now under YHWH's command.</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>Then Moses stretched out his staff toward heaven, and YHWH sent thunder and hail, and fire ran down to the earth. And YHWH rained hail upon the land of Egypt:</b> Kol (thunder/voice of YHWH) + barad (hail) + esh (fire/lightning) — the tripartite storm. The combination of lightning and hail is described in Ps 78:47-48 and 105:32-33 as the plague of hail. In ANE cosmology, the thunder-voice of a deity was the supreme expression of divine authority; Baal's 'voice' (thunder) was the central feature of Canaanite storm theology; YHWH's thunderstorm over Egypt is a direct assertion of sovereignty over the sky deities of the entire ancient Near East.</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>There was hail and fire flashing (esh mitlaqachat) continually in the midst of the hail, very heavy hail, such as had never been in all the land of Egypt since it became a nation:</b> Esh mitlaqachat = fire taking hold within itself (a Hithpael participle of laqach = to take; the fire is described as self-perpetuating within the hail). This extraordinary combination — lightning fire enclosed within hailstones — is unprecedented in natural meteorology, marking the plague as miraculous rather than merely extreme-weather. The 'never before' claim (38:24, cf. v.18) establishes the plague as historically unique in Egyptian experience.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>The hail struck down everything that was in the field in all the land of Egypt, both man and beast. And the hail struck down every plant of the field and broke every tree of the field:</b> The agricultural devastation of the hail: every plant (esev) and every tree (etz) struck down. The destruction of trees and crops directly threatened Egypt's food supply; combined with the livestock losses from the preceding plagues, the cumulative economic damage to Egypt was catastrophic. Egyptian administrative texts describe the importance of tree crops (date palms, sycamore figs) to the Egyptian economy — their destruction was not trivial.</p>",
    "26": "<p><b>Only in the land of Goshen, where the people of Israel were, was there no hail:</b> The Goshen exception continues — the geographical boundary of divine protection is maintained through the seventh plague. The hail plague is the fifth consecutive plague with explicit or implicit Goshen protection (flies, livestock, boils, hail); the spatial theology of divine protection is becoming unmistakable.</p>",
    "27": "<p><b>Then Pharaoh sent and called Moses and Aaron and said to them, 'This time I have sinned (chatati). YHWH is in the right (tzaddiq), and I and my people are in the wrong (ha-r'sha'im).'</b> The most remarkable confession in the plague narrative: Pharaoh explicitly acknowledges his sin (chatati = I have sinned), YHWH's righteousness (tzaddiq), and his own and Egypt's wickedness (r'sha'im). This is the formal theological vocabulary of covenantal acknowledgment — the same language as the Psalmist's confession (Ps 51:4: 'you are justified/tzaddiq in your words') and Dan 9:14 ('YHWH our God is righteous/tzaddiq'). Pharaoh's confession is formally correct but, as v.34-35 reveals, not genuinely penitent.</p>",
    "28": "<p><b>'Plead with YHWH, for there has been enough of God's thunder and hail. I will let you go, and you shall stay no longer.'</b> Pharaoh's promise is explicit: 'I will let you go' (ashallecha = I will send you out, the Piel of shalach). His previous offers were conditional ('if you go, not too far'); this is the most absolute promise of release yet. But it comes under the most extreme duress — the seventh plague has exceeded anything Egypt has experienced. The correlation between the severity of the plague and the completeness of Pharaoh's promise reveals that his compliance is entirely pain-driven, not theologically motivated.</p>",
    "29": "<p><b>Moses said to him, 'As soon as I have gone out of the city, I will stretch out my hands to YHWH. The thunder will cease, and there will be no more hail, so that you may know that the earth is YHWH's (la-YHWH ha'aretz).'</b> 'The earth is YHWH's' — the theological conclusion Moses draws from the hail plague. This phrase (la-YHWH ha'aretz) is the basis of Ps 24:1 ('the earth is YHWH's and the fullness thereof') and Paul's citation of it in 1 Cor 10:26. The hail plague, which controls the sky and the field, demonstrates that YHWH's sovereignty extends to all realms of the created order — not just the Nile (water), or the insects (earth's surface), but the heavens themselves.</p>",
    "30": "<p><b>'But as for you and your servants, I know that you do not yet fear YHWH God.'</b> Moses's prophetic discernment cuts through Pharaoh's confession: the fear of YHWH (yir'at YHWH) is not yet present. The confession of v.27 was accurate words without corresponding reality. 'You do not yet (terem) fear' — the 'not yet' is both diagnostic and hopeful; it implies the possibility of genuine fear at some future point. The phrase 'yet/terem' appears in contexts of unrealized potential throughout the OT.</p>",
    "31": "<p><b>The flax (pishtah) and the barley (se'orah) were struck down, for the barley was in the ear and the flax was in bud:</b> The agricultural chronology of the hail: barley (se'orah) ripening in the ear (aviv — the same word as the month name) and flax (pishtah) in bud (gibol = in bloom/bud). In Egypt, barley ripens in late February-early March; flax blooms at roughly the same time. This chronology places the seventh plague approximately one month before Passover (in the month of Aviv/Nisan = March-April), providing a rare internal calendar marker for the plague chronology. Barley and flax were two of Egypt's most economically important crops.</p>",
    "32": "<p><b>But the wheat and the emmer were not struck down, for they are late in coming up:</b> Wheat (chitah) and emmer (kussemeth) ripen 3-4 weeks after barley in the Egyptian climate — late March to April. Their survival means Egypt's primary bread crops were spared the hail damage; they would be destroyed in the subsequent locust plague (ch.10). The detail is historically specific: the hail hit between harvest cycles, destroying the early crops (barley, flax) while leaving the main food crops still in the ground. This specificity is one of the features that has led scholars to take seriously the historical memory embedded in the plague narrative.</p>",
    "33": "<p><b>So Moses went out of the city from Pharaoh and stretched out his hands to YHWH, and the thunder and the hail ceased, and the rain no longer poured upon the earth:</b> Moses prays outside the city — the prayer distance from Pharaoh and the city suggests a deliberate separation, the prophet of YHWH standing apart from the corrupt center of power. The rain (matar) cessation alongside the thunder and hail confirms that the 'hail' was part of a full storm system; Egypt genuinely received extraordinary precipitation during this plague.</p>",
    "34": "<p><b>But when Pharaoh saw that the rain and the hail and the thunder had ceased, he sinned again and hardened his heart, he and his servants:</b> The return to the hardening-after-relief pattern — despite Pharaoh's explicit confession of sin (v.27) and explicit promise of release (v.28), the cessation of distress produces re-hardening. This pattern has been consistent since the frog plague (8:15); Pharaoh's confession under duress is not conversion. The servants also harden — the institutional resistance of Egypt extends beyond the individual king to his entire court.</p>",
    "35": "<p><b>So the heart of Pharaoh was hardened, and he did not let the people of Israel go, just as YHWH had spoken through Moses:</b> The closing formula 'as YHWH had spoken through Moses' (ka'asher dibber YHWH b'yad-Moshe) ties each plague-outcome back to the original divine prediction. YHWH's foreknowledge encompasses Pharaoh's repeated re-hardening; the trajectory of the plague cycle was known to YHWH from the beginning and communicated to Moses before it began. The plague narrative is not a divine improvisation but a planned demonstration of sovereign power proceeding according to divine purpose.</p>"
  }
}

